{
  "style": "IEEE",
  "texts": [
    "Following the same procedure as in [53], we use the cross-section and forward-backward asymmetry measurements for e + e -→ µ + µ - and e + e -→ τ + τ -, as well as the differential e + e -→ e + e -data reported in [54].",
    "RG evolution is taken into account from each bin's energy up to the reference scale Λ NP = 3 TeV (see below).• Jet observables.",
    "Four-quark contact interactions are constrained using the results on the relevant combinations of SMEFT WCs provided in [26] (for four-quark operators with q L,t R) and [55] (for operators with b R, including dipoles) using LHC data.",
    "Also in this case running effects are irrelevant.JHEP03(2024)049 Numerical analysisThe first step needed to build our likelihood is to write the theory prediction for each observable in terms of SMEFT WCs at a reference high scale Λ NP, which we take to be 3 TeV.For observables with characteristic scale below the EW scale, this entails running the LEFT WCs entering the observable up to the EW scale, matching to the SMEFT, and then running in the SMEFT up to Λ NP.",
    "For LEFT running, LEFT-to-SMEFT matching, and SMEFT running, we employ DSixTools [56,57], which enables us to work analytically in the WCs also beyond the leading-logarithmic (LL) approximation."
  ],
  "correct_citations": [
    "Following the same procedure as in [53], we use the cross-section and forward-backward asymmetry measurements for e + e -→ µ + µ - and e + e -→ τ + τ -, as well as the differential e + e -→ e + e -data reported in [54].",
    "Four-quark contact interactions are constrained using the results on the relevant combinations of SMEFT WCs provided in [26] (for four-quark operators with q L,t R) and [55] (for operators with b R, including dipoles) using LHC data.",
    "For LEFT running, LEFT-to-SMEFT matching, and SMEFT running, we employ DSixTools [56,57], which enables us to work analytically in the WCs also beyond the leading-logarithmic (LL) approximation."
  ]
